The surface morphology of the prepared films was observed by atomic force microscopy (Bruker. Model: MLCT-MT-A) with scanning area of the films (2 × 2) μm2. With the excitation source (He I 21.2 eV), the ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) was used to analyze the surface of the films. UPS pressure apparatus (model; Thermo-Fisher, Escalab 250Xi, and 5 × 10−13 bar) was used in this study. Raman spectroscopy (model alpha 300 R/AS from witechulm Germany) was applied to analysis the films. The electrical conductivity of the films was measured by using (Keithley 6517 B) electrometer. By using the van der Pauw configuration, applying AC magnetic field, measurements of Hall Effect (carrier concentration and mobility carriers) were evaluated. The Seebeck coefficient of the treated CDots/PEDOT:PSS nano-composite films was measured. Keithley 616 Nanovoltmeter was used to detect the thermal output voltage (
Δ V
) [3,4], more details see supplementary materials S2. The out of plane thermal conductivity of untreated and acid treated films has been measured by using the steady state home-made device, see supplementary materials for more details (S3) and refs. [3,4]. One end of the stainless steel block was heated through the test by using a hot plate and the other was kept without heating. CDots/PDOT:PSS films were sandwiched between the two stainless steel blocks. The whole system was isolated to avoid the heat from dissipating into the surroundings. Two stainless steel blocks can be considered as heat sinks and connected with thermocouples at the block center with an interval of 5.00 ± 0.2 mm. All thermoelectric parameters of the films were measured at room temperature.

In this article, we have successfully prepared (CDots/PEDOT:PSS) nano-composite films by using the casting technique. The effect of acid treatment on the thermoelectric performance for this (CDots/PEDOT:PSS) system was briefly studied. The Seebeck coefficient of (CDots/PEDOT:PSS) films decreased with increasing the acid concentration. On the other hand, the electrical conductivity increased and the optimal value was (1753.92 ± 50 S/cm) at 10 M H2SO4 due to the growth of the carrier concentrations and carrier mobility. Also, the system (CDots/PEDOT:PSS) displays a behavior of p-type semiconductor and exhibits a high power factor (148.27 ± 20 μV/mK2) at the same concentration of H2SO4 acid. The above results were confirmed by studying UPS spectra of the films, which proved the strong effect of H2SO4 on the Fermi level of CDots/PEDOT:PSS films, and the reducing work function of CDots:PEDOT:PSS thus decreasing the Seebeck coefficient. Engineering of 5 legs flexible thermoelectric device is realized and the device was able to generate voltage (V

                        output
                     ) of 4.3 mV at a ΔT = 18 K. Also the device displayed a direct response and linear sensitivity to the ΔT. The obtained data confirmed that the resultant acid treated CDots/PEDOT:PSS nano-composite represents a great chance for future industrial applications in smart thermoelectric power devices.
